These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarómetro survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it follows attitude changes in the region.
Two related elements come from the results of this year’s survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the pretty sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
The support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries over the South Pacific circle (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from at least 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also increased in Mexico, where the economy grew up after undergoing a significant decline in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which reduces the regional average (see Table 2).
About 44% of the respondents in the region expressed themselves satisfied with the way democracy in their country was working in practice; it was the same figure as last year but with a significant increase of 25% in 2001 (graph 3)
About 34% said they had confidence in the Parliament of their country and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but a significant increase compared to 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America broke out support for democracy.
If this has been good during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many American countries have suffered only a short recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has contributed to the protection of the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased slightly only in 2009 and again fell to 32% this year.)
But the mood varies significantly from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of his outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are a widely shared feeling of progress.
