However, he clearly mentioned that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work with the international community in this field.
He noted that the Chinese climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institutional building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been achieved in all of these areas, including the approval of a new Energy Act last year, which recognizes the objectives achieved in terms of greenhouse gas reduction, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have worked in a coordinated manner with governments and locals to achieve energy savings, energy efficient use and emission reduction objectives.
In addition, it said, there are various multiannual plans ongoing or completed, both financed by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries.
For example, he mentioned the Energy Efficient Use Program, which has been implemented over the last five years and has received investment from the United Nations (UN), the government and the private initiative.
There is also a provincial climate change project, another for the change of incandescent lamps by saving lamps, and another for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
