In incandescent pumps, 95% of energy dissolves in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact pumps, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with new DEL pumps, this energy need is reduced twice.
The fluocompact ampoules last on average from 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL pumps, such as those launched by Philips manufacturing company this week - this company has also participated in the U.N. study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent pump, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
