A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the compliance with the promises of rapidly unlocked funding (the ‘speed start or early funding’) made by developed countries.
And the big French biduillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to delivering $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years and France has promised 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million euros per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU launched the big game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, big side event, brochures distribution...
Transparency is valuable and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like to do the same with all developed countries at the same level of precision.
The EU announced it had released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right path for respecting its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at it in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, be "new and additional", in order to ensure that additional effort is made without being at the expense of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million per three years for fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or in terms of public development aid.
On the contrary, France believes that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous years or to the overall level of public development aid.
Concretely, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional funding"...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
There, there is no rule, and everybody chooses their method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that a loan is equal to a given one.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is impossible to present a euro that will be recovered as an equivalent of an interest rate that is given to the euro...
But France only has such a reason: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to verify on its own.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other words) comply with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union puts €1 to satisfy its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that effort is comparable.
Nice passport tour!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scroll: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other hand on the reality of financial efforts.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it can make it believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in cohesion with its promises.
